Figure 8 presents respondents’ policy preferences related to urban mobility. There is strong support for measures that restrict car use in dense areas, enforce parking regulations, and promote walking and public transport. Respondents also express substantial support for governance tools such as park-and-ride facilities and Carbon dioxide (CO



      2


) taxation. By contrast, enthusiasm for high-technology solutions, including electric or autonomous vehicles, remains limited, reflecting skepticism toward technological fixes in a context where basic transport provision is perceived as inadequate. The most widely supported aspiration is the development of a tramway, which is viewed as a symbol of modern, collective, and more equitable mobility [23].
